{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22568"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22568"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.14,0.62,0.09,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92625"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"657"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9492"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"41638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of right-sided facial swelling and severe toothache. She reports increasing difficulty and pain with swallowing over the past day, and breathing has become difficult. Her voice is hoarse. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and is sitting forward, drooling. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 88/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 40.2\u00b0C. There is significant facial oedema on the right side, extending bilaterally below her chin, mandible and infero-lateral to her tongue. Her right lower second molar shows oedematous surrounding mucosa with purulent discharge. She can only open her mouth 15 mm between central incisors. There is a high-pitched inspiratory sound on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess","Ludwig\u0027s angina","Parapharyngeal abscess","Submandibular sialadenitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003ELudwig\u0027s angina\u003C/strong\u003E, a rapidly progressive infection involving the bilateral submandibular, sublingual and submental spaces of the floor of mouth. The characteristic findings include bilateral submandibular swelling, elevated tongue, and rapid progression, all seen in this case. The odontogenic source (lower molar) is typical, as are the systemic signs of severe infection. The key feature is the potential for airway compromise, which is evident in this case from the tripod positioning, drooling, stridor, and respiratory distress. Immediate airway management with awake fibreoptic intubation is typically required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with unilateral tonsillar swelling, uvular deviation, and trismus, but would not cause the extensive bilateral submandibular swelling seen here. Similarly, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eparapharyngeal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes unilateral neck swelling and medial tonsil displacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetropharyngeal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with neck stiffness and posterior pharyngeal wall swelling, rather than the submandibular and sublingual space involvement seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubmandibular sialadenitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with localised swelling and tenderness in the submandibular area, often associated with meals, but would not cause the extensive spread and systemic signs seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ludwig\u0027s angina is a rapidly progressive infection of the floor of mouth that can cause life-threatening airway compromise.","Signs of impending airway compromise in patients with Ludwig\u0027s angina include trismus, tripod positioning, drooling, stridor and respiratory distress.","Awake fibreoptic intubation is the preferred method of securing the airway in Ludwig\u0027s angina due to difficult anatomy and trismus."],"references":["Bridwell R, Gottlieb M, Koyfman A, Long B. Diagnosis and management of Ludwig\u0027s angina: An evidence-based review. Am J Emerg Med. 2021;41:1-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33383265/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92625"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22568"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92625"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T08:25:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T10:14:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"it